source.Name: Total population
source.Summary: Population: Total population and distribution by age and sex estimated to be consistent with the population by age and sex of the (a) 1969, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses; (b) adjusted for under/over count; (c) adjusted for age heaping; (d) adjusted for under enumeration of children under age 15; (e) 1974 Sample Census survey estimates; (f) official estimates through 2021; (g) only total population for 1963, 2022 censuses; and with estimates of the subsequent trends in fertility, mortality and international migration. In addition, the 1992, 1996, 2001-2002, 2007, 2013-2014, 2018 DHS and 1999 MICS and 2008 GFFS survey estimates have been considered.

source.Name: Total fertility rate
source.Summary: Fertility: Total fertility rate and age pattern of fertility based on: (a) official estimates of age-specific fertility rates through 2000; (b) registered births classified by age of mother and the underlying female population by age through 2017; (c) birth-histories data from the 1992, 1996, 2001-2002, 2007, 2013-2014, 2018 DHS; (d) births in the household in the preceding 12 (or 24) months classified by age of mother from the 1974 Sample Census and 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses; (e) adjusted fertility using Brass P/F ratio method (or variants) with data on children ever born and births in the preceding 12 (or 24/36) months, both classified by age of mother, from the 1969, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses; (f) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1969, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses and 1974 Sample Census and 1999 MICS and 2008 GFFS; (g) indirect estimates obtained from stable population assumption; (h) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses and 1992, 1996, 2001-2002, 2007, 2013-2014, 2018 DHS. In addition, the (a) indirect estimates obtained from the application of the reverse survival method to the 1955-2009 Education Stats; (b) cohort-completed fertility backdated by the mean age of childbearing from the 1969 Census have been considered.

source.Name: Life expectancy at birth
source.Summary: Overall Mortality: Life expectancy at birth and age pattern of mortality based on: (a) registered deaths by age and sex available through 2017; (b) The demographic impact of AIDS has been factored into the mortality estimates; (c) estimates using HIV/AIDS model life tables and estimates of under-five mortality (5q0) and adult mortality (45q15) with UNAIDS estimates of adult HIV prevalence, and ART coverage for children and adults. Mortality rates for Spectrum were calculated by removing AIM's estimates of HIV-related mortality from all-cause mortality rate estimates published in the 2024 revision of the World Population Prospects.

source.Name: Age Mortality
source.Summary: Adult and Old Age Mortality: Estimates derived from: (a) recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 1998 LCMS2 and 2003, 2005, 2009 SBS and 2006 LCMS5 and 2008 GFFS and 2010 LCMS6 and 2015-2016 SAVVY; (b) recent household deaths adjusted at adult ages for underregistration using death distribution methods; (c) siblings deaths from the 1996, 2001-2002, 2007, 2013-2014, 2018 DHS and 2000 SBS; (d) maternal orphanhood from the 1992, 1996, 2001-2002, 2007 DHS and 1999 MICS; (e) paternal orphanhood from the 1996, 2001-2002, 2007 DHS and 1999 MICS; (f) estimates of under-five, adult and old age mortality. In addition, the recent household deaths data by age and sex from the 2007 DHS and 2008 HHCS and 2010 Census have been considered.

source.Name: Infant/child mortality
source.Summary: Child Mortality: Under-five mortality based on: (a) direct estimates from births and deaths under-five calculated from full birth histories data from the 1992, 1996, 2001-2002, 2007, 2013-2014, 2018 DHS; (b) indirect estimates from data on children ever born and surviving from the 1969, 1980, 1990, 2000, 2010 censuses and 1974 Sample Census and 2007 DHS; (c) recent household deaths from the 2008 GFFS and 2015-2016 SAVVY; (d) International estimates used up to 2021. In addition, the (a) registered infant and child deaths through 2017; (b) recent household deaths from the 2007 DHS and 2008 HHCS and 2010 Census have been considered.

source.Name: International migration
source.Summary: Migration: International migration based on: (a) information on foreign-born populations from censuses and registers from major countries of destination; (b) estimates derived as the differences between overall population growth and natural increase; (c) UNHCR statistics on the number of refugees in the main countries of asylum.
